    "body": "Had a small burst of *maybe* intuition about this.\r\n\r\nWe instantiate `Peer` classes with a `reader/writer` pair which is already open.  We **only** close these in the event that the peer service is actually started.  In any case where the `Peer.run()` is never called it appears that the connection will remain open.\r\n\r\nI believe this location might be where some of these errors come from.\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/ethereum/py-evm/blob/1f60fd8576d4959c7d4642f52ac56158658cc9ae/p2p/peer.py#L130-L131\r\n\r\nIf either of the `do_p2p_handshake` or `do_sub_proto_handshake` fails I think the transport remains unclosed.\r\n\r\n@carver this **might** be more supporting evidence that the decoupling of the protocol connection from the peer concept makes sense.  ",
